import random

def unique_proteins(rng: random.Random):
    dataset = [{"Entry": i } for i in range(10)]

    num_targets = 2

    entries = []

        if entry not in entries:

        "targets": entries[:num_targets],
        "antitargets": entries[num_targets:]

When the trickster molecules started being a thing (like the molecules that had exceptionally good scores for a variety of targets) it became clear that going solely for the highest possible scores is not be the best approach because it gives us no clue about how reliable the prediction actually is. 

We will talk more in depth about it on novelty search this week, but a proxy for the reliability of predictions is the variance of scores in a set of highly similar molecules. If a region of the chemical space has high variance in scores, it's very likely that predictions will be less reliable in that region. Because of that, having a variety of medium to high scores helps in this assessment and may be a good strategy for crafting a winning submission, if the molecules you submit are in less explored regions of the dataset. The binding score is still a factor in the final score because we don't want people to submit random molecules, but it's not necessary for them to have the very best scores in all of the dataset to be useful. It is also possible to search for similar molecules to the ones previously submitted to include in future submissions, as long as your submission has some variety in order to keep a high entropy bonus
